                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d38">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.6111/232: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Russian Consul at Boston</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Conry</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="34" xml:id="d38fn34">The same telegram, <hi rend="italic"
                            >mutatis mutandis</hi>, was sent to the Russian Consuls General at
                        Chicago and Seattle (702.6111/231, 233). An acknowledgment, dated November
                        18 (702.6111/234), was received from Mr. <persName>Volkoff</persName>,
                        Russian Consul General at Chicago.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-11-17">November 17,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In view of the recognition of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics by the
                    Government of the United States, you are informed that the exequatur issued on
                    September 20, 1912, recognizing you as Consul of Russia at Boston, is revoked,
                    effective as of November 16, 1933, and that consequently your status as Russian
                    Consul is considered terminated as of that date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
